demos.solution:
To find the sum, we look at the first few powers of 2 modulo 7: \begin{align*}
2^0 &\equiv 1, \\
2^1 &\equiv 2, \\
2^2 &\equiv 4, \\
2^3 &\equiv 8 \equiv 1 \pmod{7}
\end{align*}Since $2^3 \equiv 1 \pmod{7}$, the powers of 2 modulo 7 repeat in cycles of 3.  Therefore, \begin{align*}
&1 + 2 + 2^2 + 2^3 + \dots + 2^{100} \\
&\quad\equiv 1 + 2 + 4 + 1 + 2 + 4 + \dots + 1 + 2 + 4 + 1 + 2 \\
&\quad\equiv (1 + 2 + 4) + (1 + 2 + 4) + \dots + (1 + 2 + 4) + 1 + 2 \\
&\quad\equiv \boxed{3} \pmod{7}.
\end{align*}

We must find the radius of the circle in order to find the area. We are told that points $A$ and $B$ are the endpoints of a diameter, so we use the distance formula to find the length of the diameter.

\begin{align*}
\sqrt{(-1-3)^2+(-2-2)^2} &= \sqrt{16 + 16} \\
&= 4\sqrt{2}
\end{align*}Since the diameter has a length of $4\sqrt{2}$, the radius must have length $2\sqrt{2}$. Therefore, the answer is $(2\sqrt{2})^2\pi = \boxed{8\pi}$.

