Note that the graphs of $y = x^2 + k$ and $x = y^2 + k$ are reflections of each other in the line $y = x,$ so if they are tangent to each other, then the point of tangency must lie on the line $y = x.$  Furthermore, both graphs will be tangent to the line $y = x.$

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

real func (real x) {
  return(x^2 + 1/4);
}

draw(graph(func,-2,2));
draw(reflect((0,0),(1,1))*graph(func,-2,2));
draw((-2,-2)--(4,4),dashed);

label("$y = x$", (4,4), NE);
label("$y = x^2 + k$", (2,4 + 1/4), N);
label("$x = y^2 + k$", (4 + 1/4,2), E);
[/asy]

This means that the quadratic $x^2 + k = x$ will have a double root.  We can arrange the equation to get
\[x^2 - x + k = 0.\]We want the discriminant of this quadratic to be 0, giving us $1 - 4k = 0,$ or $k = \boxed{\frac{1}{4}}.$

We have  \begin{align*}
\frac{12}{x \cdot x} \cdot \frac{x^4}{14x}\cdot \frac{35}{3x} &=
\frac{12 \cdot x^4 \cdot 35}{x^2\cdot 14x \cdot 3x}\\& = \frac{(4 \cdot 3) \cdot (5 \cdot 7) \cdot x^4}{(3 \cdot 2 \cdot 7)(x^2 \cdot x \cdot x)}\\
&= \frac{2\cdot 2 \cdot 3 \cdot 5 \cdot 7}{2 \cdot 3 \cdot 7}\cdot\frac{x^4}{x^{4}}\\
&= 2 \cdot 5 = \boxed{10}.
\end{align*}

solution:
Let $j$ be John's age and $d$ be his dad's age. We are trying to find the value of $d$. We can create a system of two equations to represent the given information. They are

\begin{align*}
j &= d - 31 \\
j + d &= 53 \\
\end{align*}

We want to find $d$, so we need to eliminate $j$ from the equations above. Substituting the first equation into the second to eliminate $j$, we have $(d-31)+d=53$, or $d=42$. Thus, John's dad is $\boxed{42}$ years old.

